{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UZtYz3zeEYnchX2tCxH5To","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here is a summary of the results:\n\n---\n\n## Results Summary\n\n### Cluster Status\n- Spark master and worker pods: both **Running**\n- All 3 benchmark jobs: **Complete**\n\n### Performance Comparison\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed Time | Technique | Benefit |\n|----------|-------------|-----------|---------|\n| **Baseline** | 31.75s | Skewed shuffle join | None — straggler partitions |\n| **Broadcast Join** | 13.81s | Broadcast small table, no shuffle | No shuffle, no skew (**2.3x faster**) |\n| **AQE** | 17.10s | Adaptive query execution, auto-split hot partitions | Auto-splits skewed partitions (**1.86x faster**) |\n\n### Skew Profile (same across all runs — input data)\n- Skew ratio: **44x** (max partition 11,579 rows vs min 263 rows)\n- Hot products 1–5 each have 5,000 orders; all others have ~263\n\n### Key Takeaways\n- **Broadcast join** was the fastest (13.81s) because it eliminates the shuffle entirely by broadcasting the small `products` table to all workers — skew in the join key becomes irrelevant.\n- **AQE** (17.10s) is more general: Spark detects skewed partitions at runtime and automatically splits them, reducing straggler impact without requiring the developer to know the data distribution ahead of time.\n- Both strategies beat the baseline by roughly 2x on this workload.\n\nAll success criteria are met: baseline completed (with observed skew), both optimization strategies applied and completed successfully."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3005,"cache_read_input_tokens":29347,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3005},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management